                'title' => 'Being Online Isn’t Enough',
                'excerpt' => 'Many businesses are visible online but still struggle to generate enquiries. This article breaks down how people really move from discovering you to contacting you — and where most online setups quietly fail.',
                'content' => '<h2>Being Online Isn’t Enough - and That’s the Real Problem</h2>

                <p>Most businesses today have an online presence of some kind. A Facebook page. An Instagram account. Maybe even a website.</p>

                <p>And yet, a common frustration keeps coming up:</p>

                <p><em>“We’re visible, but it’s not really bringing in clients.”</em></p>

                <p>The issue usually isn’t effort or intent. It’s structure. Being online is only the starting point — what matters is how everything connects.</p>

                <h3>1. Likes Feel Like Progress — But Rarely Create Leads</h3>

                <p>Social media makes it easy to feel productive. Likes, comments, and shares look like momentum.</p>

                <p>But attention without direction doesn’t create business. A post can perform well and still lead to zero enquiries if there’s no clear next step.</p>

                <p>Likes are not leads. They’re a signal that someone noticed you — not that they know what to do next.</p>

                <h3>2. Social Media Is Borrowed Space</h3>

                <p>Social platforms are useful, but they’re not owned assets. You don’t control the algorithm, the reach, or the rules — and they can change overnight.</p>

                <p>That doesn’t mean social media should be ignored. It means it should be treated as a pathway, not a destination.</p>

                <p>Strong online setups use social platforms to guide people somewhere more stable.</p>

                <h3>3. Your Website Is the Home Base</h3>

                <p>A website should sit at the centre of your online presence.</p>

                <p>Unlike social posts, it doesn’t disappear. Unlike platforms, it doesn’t shift the rules. Over time, it builds familiarity, trust, and clarity.</p>

                <p>When everything points back to a well-structured website, your online efforts start working together instead of competing.</p>

                <h3>4. Google Signals Intent, Not Curiosity</h3>

                <p>People scroll social media to be entertained or distracted.</p>

                <p>They use Google when they want to solve a problem, compare options, or hire someone.</p>

                <p>This difference matters. Someone searching has intent, which means your website and messaging often matter more than posting frequency.</p>

                <h3>5. Discovery Happens Before Contact</h3>

                <p>Before reaching out, most people quietly check you out.</p>

                <ul>
                <li>They Google your business</li>
                <li>They visit your website</li>
                <li>They look for reassurance that you’re legitimate</li>
                </ul>

                <p>This happens even when someone was referred to you. If what they find feels unclear, outdated, or inconsistent, they often move on — without saying a word.</p>

                <h3>6. The Simple Funnel Most Businesses Already Have</h3>

                <p>Here’s the overlooked truth: most businesses already have a funnel.</p>

                <p>It just isn’t connected.</p>

                <p><strong>Discover → Check → Decide → Contact</strong></p>

                <p>When your social media, website, and contact points support this flow, enquiries feel natural. When they don’t, you’re left guessing where things went wrong.</p>

                <h3>Conclusion</h3>

                <p>Being online isn’t about being everywhere or posting constantly.</p>

                <p>It’s about making it easy for the right people to understand what you do, trust you, and take the next step.</p>

                <p>When those pieces are aligned, your online presence stops feeling noisy — and starts becoming useful.</p>',
